{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 15:31:45.371569", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — Clos EBGP lab\nSummary\n- Overall control-plane (BGP) appears functional across the fabric, and most host-to-host pings succeed.\n- One host subnet (10.0.0.0/24 — pc_0_0) is isolated: many hosts cannot reach 10.0.0.2 (pc_0_0).\n- The problem localizes to leaf_router_0_0. A static Null/blackhole route for 10.0.0.0/30 is configured there (ip route 10.0.0.0/30 Null0). This more-specific route causes traffic toward 10.0.0.2 to be dropped in the kernel/data plane and prevents ARP/host-level forwarding — explaining the observed isolation.\n\nObserved anomalies (symptoms)\n1) Reachability scan (all hosts → all hosts)\n- Many sources show successful pings generally, but pings to 10.0.0.2 (pc_0_0) are consistently failing/unknown.\n- Examples of hosts that had unreachable/unknown status when targeting pc_0_0:\n  - pc_1_2 → 10.0.0.2 (status: unknown)\n  - pc_1_0 → 10.0.0.2 (unknown)\n  - pc_1_3 → 10.0.0.2 (unknown)\n  - pc_1_1 → 10.0.0.2 (unknown)\n  - pc_0_1 → 10.0.0.2 (unknown)\n  - pc_0_2 → 10.0.0.2 (unknown)\n  - pc_0_3 → 10.0.0.2 (unknown)\n  - Several other intra-pod/intra-fabric pings are OK (loss 0%, normal RTTs).\n\n2) Host pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2)\n- ifconfig/ip output:\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.0.2/24\n  - RX packets 0 bytes 0, TX packets 0 bytes 0 — host saw no traffic on its interface.\n- Default route: via 10.0.0.1 (leaf_router_0_0).\n\n3) leaf_router_0_0\n- Interface eth4 is configured with 10.0.0.1/24 and shows state UP/LOWER_UP, but:\n  - eth4: RX packets 0 TX packets 0 (no L2 traffic observed on that interface).\n- Kernel routing table (ip route) contains:\n  - blackhole 10.0.0.0/30 proto static metric 20\n  - 10.0.0.0/24 dev eth4 proto kernel scope link src 10.0.0.1\n  - plus many BGP-learned next-hops for remote prefixes\n- FRR running config shows an explicit static route:\n  - ip route 10.0.0.0/30 Null0\n- FRR BGP on leaf_router_0_0 is advertising network 10.0.0.0/24 in BGP (so control-plane origination exists), but the kernel/data-plane static Null route is present too.\n\nLocalization — faulty device(s)\n- Primary: leaf_router_0_0\n  - Evidence: explicit ip route 10.0.0.0/30 Null0 in running config; corresponding blackhole route present in kernel routing table; interface eth4 shows no packets; other fabrics can reach other subnets but not 10.0.0.2.\n- Affected endpoint: pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2) — symptomatically isolated; interface shows no RX/TX.\n\nRoot-cause analysis\n- The immediate root cause is the presence of a static Null/blackhole route for 10.0.0.0/30 installed on leaf_router_0_0 (ip route 10.0.0.0/30 Null0).\n- Why this causes isolation:\n  - The kernel route for 10.0.0.0/30 is more specific than 10.0.0.0/24 and matches traffic toward 10.0.0.2. That blackhole route causes the kernel to drop packets destined for addresses in that /30 (including 10.0.0.2) before they can be resolved/forwarded to the local interface.\n  - Because traffic is discarded by the blackhole, ARP resolution and Layer-2 traffic toward the host do not occur — explaining the zero RX/TX counters on both the leaf's eth4 and the host's eth0.\n- Control-plane vs data-plane:\n  - BGP configuration on leaf_router_0_0 includes network 10.0.0.0/24, so the prefix is advertised in BGP (control-plane), but the data-plane kernel/static route prevents actual packet delivery to the host. Thus the control-plane advertisement does not reflect usable connectivity in the data plane.\n\nImpact and scope\n- Impacted: host pc_0_0 and any services running on 10.0.0.0/24 as reachable via leaf_router_0_0's eth4.\n- Reachability: All other tested hosts and subnets (10.0.1.0/24, 10.0.2.0/24, 10.1.x.0/24, etc.) appear reachable; this is an isolated outage affecting only the 10.0.0.0/24 host(s) served by leaf_router_0_0.\n- BGP control-plane remains up (peers present), so routing advertisements exist but are not matched by a usable data-plane path for the affected host due to the local blackhole.\n\nRelevant evidence (excerpts)\n- leaf_router_0_0 running-config/top lines:\n  - ip route 10.0.0.0/30 Null0\n  - router bgp 65200\n    - address-family ipv4 unicast\n      - network 10.0.0.0/24\n- leaf_router_0_0 ip route shows:\n  - blackhole 10.0.0.0/30 proto static metric 20\n  - 10.0.0.0/24 dev eth4 proto kernel scope link src 10.0.0.1\n- pc_0_0 ifconfig:\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.0.2/24, RX packets 0 TX packets 0\n- leaf_router_0_0 eth4 counters:\n  - eth4: inet 10.0.0.1/24, RX packets 0 TX packets 0\n- Reachability scan: pings to 10.0.0.2 returned unknown/unreachable from many hosts while other pairs returned 0% loss.\n\nConclusion\n- The outage of pc_0_0 is caused by a local data-plane blackhole on leaf_router_0_0 (static Null0 route for 10.0.0.0/30). This misconfiguration results in dropped packets destined for the host subnet and prevents L2 traffic/ARP between the leaf and pc_0_0, despite BGP advertisements for the /24 being present.\n- Fault is localized to leaf_router_0_0 (configuration) with symptomatic isolation of pc_0_0.\n\nIf you want, I can:\n- show the exact lines from the leaf_router_0_0 routing table and running-config again,\n- run targeted pings/traces from leaf_router_0_0 and/from neighboring spine/router to further demonstrate packet drops,\n- or run additional diagnostics (ARP table, vtysh show ip route detail, show ip bgp) to collect more confirmation evidence.\n\n(Per your instruction I have not provided mitigation steps; this report focuses on detection, localization, and root-cause identification.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 16238, "output_tokens": 3275, "total_tokens": 19513, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 15872}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1600}}}
